  "prompt": "Do Las Vegas Casinos pump oxygen into the air conditioning systems? Why?",
  "response": "This is a common myth about Las Vegas casinos. While it's often claimed that casinos pump oxygen into their air conditioning systems to keep gamblers alert and spending money, this is not actually true. \n\nThere's no scientific evidence that casinos deliberately add extra oxygen to their air conditioning systems. This urban legend has been circulating for years, but it's been debunked by casino employees, managers, and independent researchers.\n\nCasinos do use various psychological and environmental techniques to keep gamblers comfortable and engaged, such as:\n- Controlled temperature\n- Lack of windows or clocks\n- Constant background noise\n- Free drinks\n- Bright, stimulating lighting\n\nBut deliberately pumping oxygen is not one of these techniques. In fact, doing so would be:\n- Extremely expensive\n- Potentially dangerous (increased oxygen levels can be a fire hazard)\n- Likely to violate building and safety codes\n\nThe myth likely persists because it seems plausible and fits into the narrative of casinos using sneaky tactics to keep people gambling.",
